# Split the data into separate datasets for 2018 and 2019
df_2018 = df[df['pk_partition'].dt.year == 2018]
df_2019 = df[df['pk_partition'].dt.year == 2019]

# Create rolling window statistics for finance products in 2018
savings_windows = [3] # Change as desired
for col in df_2018.columns:
    if col in finance_products:
        for window in savings_windows:
            df_2018[f'{col}_mean_{window}'] = df_2018.groupby(['pk_cid'])[col].rolling(window).mean().values
            df_2018[f'{col}_std_{window}'] = df_2018.groupby(['pk_cid'])[col].rolling(window).std().values

# Create rolling window statistics for saving products in 2019
for col in df_2019.columns:
    if col in savings_products:
        for window in savings_windows:
            df_2019[f'{col}_mean_{window}'] = df_2019.groupby(['pk_cid'])[col].rolling(window).mean().values
            df_2019[f'{col}_std_{window}'] = df_2019.groupby(['pk_cid'])[col].rolling(window).std().values

# Define a function to count the number of unique customers for each entry channel and year
def count_customers_by_entry_channel_year(df, year):
    # Filter the data frame for the given year
    df['pk_partition'] = pd.to_datetime(df['pk_partition'])
    df_year = df[df['pk_partition'].dt.year == year]
    # Count the number of unique customers for each entry channel
    counts = df_year[df_year[['em_acount', 'em_account_pp', 'emc_account', 'em_account_p', 'payroll_account', 'debit_card']].gt(0).any(axis=1)].groupby('entry_channel')['pk_cid'].nunique()
    # Return a dictionary with the counts for each entry channel and year
    return dict(zip(counts.index, counts.values))

# Count the number of unique customers for each entry channel and year
entry_channel_counts_2018 = count_customers_by_entry_channel_year(df_2018_ch, 2018)
entry_channel_counts_2019 = count_customers_by_entry_channel_year(df_2019_ch, 2019)

# Replace the name of each entry channel by the count number in df_2018 and df_2019
df_2018['entry_channel_count'] = df_2018['entry_channel'].map(entry_channel_counts_2018)
df_2019['entry_channel_count'] = df_2019['entry_channel'].map(entry_channel_counts_2019)

# Define the thresholds for which to print highly correlated features
thresholds = [0.9, 0.7, 0.5]

# Loop through the thresholds and print the highly correlated features for each threshold
for threshold in thresholds:
    # Filter the correlation matrix to only show highly correlated features
    high_corr_features = []
    for i in range(len(corr_matrix.columns)):
        for j in range(i):
            if abs(corr_matrix.iloc[i, j]) > threshold:
                colname = corr_matrix.columns[i]
                high_corr_features.append(colname)

    # Print the list of highly correlated features for the current threshold
    print(f"Highly correlated features for threshold {threshold}: {high_corr_features}\n")
